%N A393471 The radical value of the product of adjacent terms of A392505.
%C A393471 For n <= 2^14, the only primes in the sequence are {2, 3, 5, 11}. Apart from 2, these primes are followed by their squares in A393471. These may be the only primes in this sequence. - _Michael De Vlieger_, Mar 24 2026
%H A393471 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A393471/b393471.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A393471 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A393471/a393471.png">Log log scatterplot of a(n)</a>, n = 1..2^14, showing primes in red and squarefree composites in other colors. Terms in yellow are even squarefree semiprimes and terms in light green are odd squarefree semiprimes, appearing in two increasingly well defined trajectories near the bottom of the graph.
%H A393471 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A393471/a393471_1.png">Image of the first 100000 terms</a>.
%F A393471 a(n) = A007947(A392505(n)*A392505(n+1)). - _Michael De Vlieger_, Mar 24 2026
%t A393471 Block[{c, q}, nn = 120; c[_] := False; q[_] := False; Set[{i, j}, {1, 2}]; u = 3; MapIndexed[Set[{c[#], q[#]}, {True, True}] &, {1, 2}]; rad[x] := Times @@ FactorInteger[x][[All, 1]]; {i, j}~Join~Reap[Do[If[PrimePowerQ[j], p = FactorInteger[j][[1, 1]]; k = 1; While[Or[c[#], q[rad[j*#] ] ] &[p*k], k++]; k *= p, k = u; While[Or[c[k], q[rad[j*k] ], CoprimeQ[j, k] ], k++] ]; Sow[rad[j*k] ]; Set[{q[rad[j*k] ], c[k], i, j}, {True, True, j, k}]; If[k == u, While[c[u], u++]], {n, 3, nn}] ][[-1, 1]] ] (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Mar 24 2026 *)
